{"Version":2,"Notebooks":{"4":{"id":4,"Name":"Interconexi√≥n de redes","Description":"Redes 2, CCNA R&S: Routing and Switching Essentials"}},"Notes":{"5":{"id":5,"Title":"Chapter 1","Content":"<h1>Chapter 1</h1><h1>Introduction to Switched Networks</h1><h2>Growing Complexity of Networks</h2><div><ul><li>Our <i>digital world</i> is <i>changing</i>.</li><ul><li>In today's globalized workplace, employees can access resources from anywhere in the world and info must be available at any time, and on any device.</li><li>Requirements [:long-arrow-right:] Need to build next-gen networks that are secure, reliable, and highly available.</li></ul></ul><h2>Elements of a Converged Network</h2></div><div><ul><li>To support <i>collaboration</i>, business networks employ converged solutions using <b>voice systems</b>, IP phones, voice gateways, video support, and video conferencing.</li></ul><div><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/560b890b-28eb-42da-b743-40e13d7d2766\" alt=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-YIgySnorGDo/V7J2Gi1VSGI/AAAAAAAAOD4/B5fW2ZZ8xAonFLLUhhJ2nSX1QLwFWVAywCLcB/s1600/1.1.1.2.png\" data-url=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-YIgySnorGDo/V7J2Gi1VSGI/AAAAAAAAOD4/B5fW2ZZ8xAonFLLUhhJ2nSX1QLwFWVAywCLcB/s1600/1.1.1.2.png\"><br></div></div><div><ul><li>A converged network with collaboration support may include features such as:</li><ul><li><b>Call control</b> - Telephone call processing, caller ID, call transfer, hold, and conference.</li><li><b>Voice messaging</b> - Voicemail</li><li><b>Mobility</b> - Receive important calls wherever you are</li><li><b>Automated attendant</b> - Serve customers faster by routing calls directly to the right department or individual</li></ul><li>One primary benefit is that there is just one physical network to install and manage.</li><ul><li>Substantial savings over the installation and management of separate voice, video, and data networks.</li><li>Such a converged network solution integrates IT management so that any moves, additions, and changes are completed with an intuitive management interface.</li><li>Also <i>provides</i> <b>PC softphone application support</b>, as well as <b>point-to-point video</b>.</li></ul><li>Resulted in an evolution in networks <i>from</i>&nbsp;<i>a traditional data transport</i>&nbsp;role, <i>to</i> <i>a </i><b style=\"font-style: italic;\">super-highway for data, voice, and video</b><i>&nbsp;communication.</i>&nbsp;</li></ul><h2>Cisco Borderless Networks</h2></div><div><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">With the increasing demands of the converged network, the network must be developed with an architectural approach that embeds intelligence, simplifies operations, and is scalable to meet future demands.</span><br></li><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">It is a network architecture </span><i style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">combining</i><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> </span><i style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"><u>innovation</u></i><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> and </span><i style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"><u>design</u></i><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> that allows organizations to support a </span><i style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">borderless network</i><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> that can </span><b style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">connect anyone, anywhere, anytime, on any device - securely, reliably, and seamlessly</b><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">.&nbsp;</span><br></li><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Provides the framework to unify wired and wireless access, including policy, access control, and performance management across many different device types.</span><br></li></ul></div><div><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/8ac1fae8-2ea7-46b2-a5a5-509470b93f85\" alt=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-OdGEr_gDc80/V7J2Hqa6oqI/AAAAAAAAOEA/3vJGSSYKH946PH0IDbY9ZNzsOMQkwzMiwCLcB/s1600/1.1.1.3.png\" data-url=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-OdGEr_gDc80/V7J2Hqa6oqI/AAAAAAAAOEA/3vJGSSYKH946PH0IDbY9ZNzsOMQkwzMiwCLcB/s1600/1.1.1.3.png\"><br></div><div><ul><li>By combining this hardware infrastructure with policy-based software solutions, the Cisco Borderless Network provides two primary sets of services:</li><ul><li>Network services and user</li><li>Endpoint services</li></ul><li>It enables different network elements to work together and allow users to access resources from anyplace at any time, while providing optimization, scalability, and security.</li></ul><h2>Hierarchy in the Borderless Switched Network</h2></div><div>Creating a borderless switched network requires that sound network design principles are used to ensure maximum availability, flexibility, security, and manageability.</div><div>The borderless switched network must deliver on current requirements and future required services and technologies. Their design guidelines are built upon the following principles:</div><div><ul><li><b>Hierarchical</b> - <i>Facilitates understanding the role of each device</i> at every tier, simplifies deployment, operation, and management, and reduces fault domains at every tier. Helps for every device on every tier to employ a specific role.</li><li><b>Modularity </b>- <i>Allows</i> seamless <i>network expansion</i> and integrated service enablement on an <i>on-demand basis</i>.</li><li><b>Resiliency </b>- <i>Satisfies user expectations</i> for keeping the network always on. Provides a way &nbsp;for the network to always be accessible.</li><li><b>Flexibility </b>- <i>Allows intelligent traffic load sharing</i> by using all network resources. Uses all network resources available to provide data traffic load sharing.</li></ul></div><div>These <b>ARE NOT independent principles.</b></div><div>Understanding how each principle fits in the context of the others is critical.</div><div>Designing a borderless switched network in a hierarchical fashion creates a foundation that <i>allows networks designers</i>&nbsp;to overlay <b>security, mobility, and unified communication features</b>.</div><div>Two time-tested and proven hierarchical design frameworks for campus networks are the three-tier layer and the two-tier layer models:</div><div><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/5b7b2d40-9866-45dd-a2d3-e09299eeb5da\" alt=\"https://4.bp.blogspot.com/-d4HgDXy1eLc/V7J2HlIWtVI/AAAAAAAAOD8/AfyShREaWvgYym6XXU760wOQSm6vsx_YQCLcB/s1600/1.1.1.4.1.png\" data-url=\"https://4.bp.blogspot.com/-d4HgDXy1eLc/V7J2HlIWtVI/AAAAAAAAOD8/AfyShREaWvgYym6XXU760wOQSm6vsx_YQCLcB/s1600/1.1.1.4.1.png\"><br></div><div><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/c2cff220-225b-4350-8212-38a9d1824e40\" alt=\"https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-EtlX_tp-PzA/V7J2Hk8CutI/AAAAAAAAOEE/VsoHAngtKZwzflrZr8qp4P2zIoTe-uwmwCLcB/s1600/1.1.1.4.2.png\" data-url=\"https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-EtlX_tp-PzA/V7J2Hk8CutI/AAAAAAAAOEE/VsoHAngtKZwzflrZr8qp4P2zIoTe-uwmwCLcB/s1600/1.1.1.4.2.png\"><br></div><div>The three critical layers within these tiered designs are the <b>access, distribution, and core layers</b>. <i>Each layer can be seen as a</i> <b>well-defined, structured module with specific roles and functions</b> in the campus network.&nbsp;</div><h2>Access, Distribution, and Core Layers</h2><div><ul><li><b>Access Layer</b></li><ul><li>Represents the network edge, where traffic enters or exits the campus network.</li><li>Primary function is to provide network access to the user.</li><li><i>Access layer switches</i>&nbsp;connect to <i>distribution layer switches</i>, which implement network foundation technologies such as <b>routing, quality of service, </b>and <b>security</b>.</li><li>The next-gen switching platforms now provide more converged, integrated, and intelligent services to various types of endpoints at the network edge.</li></ul><li><b>Distribution Layer</b>&nbsp;</li><ul><li>Interfaces <i>between the access layer</i> and <i>the core layer</i>&nbsp;to provide many important functions:</li><ul><li>Aggregating large-scale wiring closet networks.</li><li>Aggregating <u>Layer 2 broadcast domains and Layer 3 routing boundaries</u>.</li><li>Providing intelligent switching, routing, and network access <u>policy functions</u> to access the rest of the network.</li><li>Providing <u>high availability through redundant</u> distribution layer switches to the end-user and <u>equal cost paths</u> to the core.</li><li>Providing differentiated services to various classes of service applications at the edge of the network.</li></ul></ul><li><b>Core Layer</b>&nbsp;</li><ul><li><b>Network backbone</b>.</li><li>Connects several layers of the campus network.</li><li><u>Primary purpose</u> is to <b>provide fault isolation and high-speed backbone connectivity</b>.</li></ul></ul><div><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/a5c1ac29-8985-4a65-ab6b-bab3930cb7f8\" alt=\"https://4.bp.blogspot.com/-bhn3yxiXLaw/V7J2JBqGBHI/AAAAAAAAOEI/mopzLOXTiLwtZzx3m4jYX7exjdP8N0VSACLcB/s1600/1.1.1.5.1.png\" data-url=\"https://4.bp.blogspot.com/-bhn3yxiXLaw/V7J2JBqGBHI/AAAAAAAAOEI/mopzLOXTiLwtZzx3m4jYX7exjdP8N0VSACLcB/s1600/1.1.1.5.1.png\"><br></div></div><div><ul><ul><li>(above) <b>Three-tier campus</b> network design for organizations where the <u>access, distribution, and core</u> are each <u>separate layers</u>.&nbsp;</li><li>In some cases</li></ul></ul><div><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/11f110a0-ef3a-4d64-ace0-b89e006fcb24\" alt=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-kXHFnsFvYvQ/V7J2JFccnVI/AAAAAAAAOEM/LUEsx7di0h0Mjx8btf1NupWq5j_0RbG1gCLcB/s1600/1.1.1.5.2.png\" data-url=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-kXHFnsFvYvQ/V7J2JFccnVI/AAAAAAAAOEM/LUEsx7di0h0Mjx8btf1NupWq5j_0RbG1gCLcB/s1600/1.1.1.5.2.png\"><br></div></div><div><ul><ul><li>(above) <b>Two-tier campus network</b> design for an enterprise campus where the <u>distribution and core layers</u> are <u>collapsed into a single layer</u>.</li></ul></ul><div><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/32e69755-84f0-4219-9b8f-6840a4045706\" alt=\"https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-07jhYkfy6dk/V7J2JIc_6WI/AAAAAAAAOEQ/riCXFv3wll84JcdTH3_uyQKUWRoBmP_9gCLcB/s1600/1.1.1.6%2Bexercise.png\" data-url=\"https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-07jhYkfy6dk/V7J2JIc_6WI/AAAAAAAAOEQ/riCXFv3wll84JcdTH3_uyQKUWRoBmP_9gCLcB/s1600/1.1.1.6%2Bexercise.png\"><br></div></div><h2>Role of Switched Networks</h2><div><ul><li>Has evolved dramatically in the last two decades.</li><ul><li>It was not long ago that flat Layer 2 switched networks were the norm. Flat Layer 2 data networks relied on the basic properties of Ethernet and the widespread use of hub repeaters to propagate LAN traffic throughout an organization.</li></ul><li><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/4839d222-74b9-4e43-b0ae-62e1f6a191f8\" alt=\"https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-e7578K2yBD4/V7J2Jc61BwI/AAAAAAAAOEU/tGuKIp5q8eUFjudiSLb1oZczGbZhYB68ACLcB/s1600/1.1.2.1.1.png\" data-url=\"https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-e7578K2yBD4/V7J2Jc61BwI/AAAAAAAAOEU/tGuKIp5q8eUFjudiSLb1oZczGbZhYB68ACLcB/s1600/1.1.2.1.1.png\"><br></li><li>Networks have fundamentally <b>changed to switched LANs</b> in a hierarchical network. A&nbsp;<i>switched LAN</i>&nbsp;allows more flexibility, traffic management, and additional features:</li><ul><li><b>Quality of service</b></li><li><b>Additional security</b></li><li><u>Support for</u> <b>wireless networking and connectivity</b></li><li><u>Support for</u> <b>new technologies</b>, such as IP telephony and mobility services</li></ul></ul><div><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/79c802ff-0d58-4784-8327-2591a4bae168\" alt=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-ZmgsphRT6pM/V7J2LcZ0ubI/AAAAAAAAOEc/FJTlljy4-iUKCmrbgOfXw4rcs4Qvp7legCLcB/s1600/1.1.2.1.2.png\" data-url=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-ZmgsphRT6pM/V7J2LcZ0ubI/AAAAAAAAOEc/FJTlljy4-iUKCmrbgOfXw4rcs4Qvp7legCLcB/s1600/1.1.2.1.2.png\"><br></div></div><h2>Form Factors</h2><div>Various types of switches used in business networks. It is important to deploy the appropriate types of switches based on network requirements.</div><div><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/bfcbf650-e030-41d1-9e26-826888afd197\" alt=\"https://4.bp.blogspot.com/-v6CrPTn03hw/V7J2LTpwCFI/AAAAAAAAOEY/Cdc_vAxuMhw0J7_zUTk376SgRiEnVD2VgCLcB/s1600/1.1.2.2.1.png\" data-url=\"https://4.bp.blogspot.com/-v6CrPTn03hw/V7J2LTpwCFI/AAAAAAAAOEY/Cdc_vAxuMhw0J7_zUTk376SgRiEnVD2VgCLcB/s1600/1.1.2.2.1.png\"><br></div><div><u>When selecting the type of switch</u>, the <u>network designer must <b>choose</b></u> between a <i>fixed or a modular</i> <i>configuration</i>, and <i>stackable or non-stackable</i>.</div><div>Another one is the thickness of the switch, expressed in the number of rack units. Important for switches mounted in a rack.</div><div><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/1e551a55-66df-4dee-b3d6-c50b6af7cad7\" alt=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-D5YM1vmcp6M/V7J2LS9kN-I/AAAAAAAAOEg/7LoeJZca2looE8orALfihozAa5WC4tg1gCLcB/s1600/1.1.2.2.2.png\" data-url=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-D5YM1vmcp6M/V7J2LS9kN-I/AAAAAAAAOEg/7LoeJZca2looE8orALfihozAa5WC4tg1gCLcB/s1600/1.1.2.2.2.png\"><br></div><h4>Fixed Configuration Switches</h4><div><strike>Do not support features or options <b>beyond</b></strike>&nbsp;<b>those that originally came</b> with the switch.</div><div>The particular model determines the features and options available.</div><h4>Modular Configuration Switches</h4><div>Offer <b>more flexibility</b> in their configuration.</div><div>Typically come with different sized chassis that allow for the installation of <i>different numbers</i> of <b>modular line cards</b>.</div><div><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/71b0bc01-8493-45d9-8832-200bedb24265\" alt=\"https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-lX66VJNh0c0/V7J2LmiDlJI/AAAAAAAAOEk/wx3XaZ95tgMR2jSUR84q1r1FBKnvUh_pACLcB/s1600/1.1.2.2.3.png\" data-url=\"https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-lX66VJNh0c0/V7J2LmiDlJI/AAAAAAAAOEk/wx3XaZ95tgMR2jSUR84q1r1FBKnvUh_pACLcB/s1600/1.1.2.2.3.png\"><br></div><div>The <i>line cards</i>&nbsp;actually <u>contain the ports</u>. The larger the chassis, the more modules it can support.</div><h4>Stackable Configuration Switches</h4><div>Can be <b>interconnected</b> using a <b>special cable</b> that <u>provides high-bandwidth</u> throughput between the switches.</div><div><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/356d9063-9cc6-4b41-8b4f-626327e410fc\" alt=\"https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-_Ln6lm3i8GA/V7J2LjZGvvI/AAAAAAAAOEo/NHyNN1n3ZZgEBz7O1hfVGqmJbfW6XFOWwCLcB/s1600/1.1.2.2.4.png\" data-url=\"https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-_Ln6lm3i8GA/V7J2LjZGvvI/AAAAAAAAOEo/NHyNN1n3ZZgEBz7O1hfVGqmJbfW6XFOWwCLcB/s1600/1.1.2.2.4.png\"><br></div><div>Cisco StackWise technology allows the interconnection of up to nine switches.</div><div><u>The stacked switches effectively operate as a single larger switch</u>. They are <b>desirable</b> where <u>fault tolerance and bandwidth availability are <b>critical</b></u> and a <i>modular switch</i> is <i>too costly</i> to implement.</div><div>Using <u>cross-connected connections</u>, the <i>network</i> can <b><i>recover quickly</i></b> if a single switch fails. Stackable switches use a <i>special port for interconnections</i>.</div><div><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/e03f65a9-048d-4936-b147-e685d500735e\" alt=\"https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-5m4Nm81_Akk/V7J2LtgUHEI/AAAAAAAAOEs/dzDP1hmoz_8JFX8je-uEVECfwfBTRgYsACLcB/s1600/1.1.2.3.png\" data-url=\"https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-5m4Nm81_Akk/V7J2LtgUHEI/AAAAAAAAOEs/dzDP1hmoz_8JFX8je-uEVECfwfBTRgYsACLcB/s1600/1.1.2.3.png\"><br></div><h2>Switching as a General Concept in Networking and Telecommunications</h2><div>The concept of switching and forwarding frames is universal in networking and telecommunications.</div><div>The fundamental concept of switching refers to a device making a decision based on two criteria:</div><div><ul><li>Ingress port</li><li>Destination address</li></ul><div>The <u>decision on how a switch forwards traffic</u> is made in <u>relation to the flow of that traffic</u>.</div></div><div><ul><li><b>Ingress</b> is used to describe where a frame enters the device on a port.</li><li><b>Egress</b> is used to describe frames leaving the device from a particular port.</li></ul><div>When a <u>switch makes a decision</u>, it is <b>based</b> on the <u>ingress port</u> and the <u>destination address of the message</u>.</div></div><div>&lt;image 1.2.1.1&gt;</div><div><ol><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">If a message enters switch port 1 and has a destination address of EA, then the switch forwards the traffic out port 4.&nbsp;</span><br></li><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">If a message enters switch port 5 and has a destination address of EE, then the switch forwards the traffic out port 1.&nbsp;</span><br></li><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">If a message enters switch port 3 and has a destination address of AB, then the switch forwards the traffic out port 6.</span><br></li></ol><div>Only intelligence of the LAN switch is its ability to use its table to forward traffic based on the ingress port and the destination address of a message.</div></div><div>There's <i><u>only one</u></i> <b>master switching table</b>&nbsp;that describes a strict association between addresses and ports.</div><div><i>Cisco LAN switches forward Ethernet frames based on the destination MAC address of the frames.</i>&nbsp;</div><h2>Dynamically Populating a Switch MAC Address Table</h2><div><u><b>Switches</b> use MAC addresses</u> to direct network communications through the switch to the appropriate port toward the destination.</div><div><ul><li>It is made up of integrated circuits and the accompanying software that controls the data paths through the switch.</li><li><i><u>To know</u></i> which port to use to transmit a frame, it must <i><u>first learn</u></i> which devices exist on each port.</li><li>As it learns the relationship of ports to devices, it builds a table called a <b>MAC address</b>, or <b>content addressable memory</b> (<b>CAM</b>) table.</li><ul><li><i>CAM</i> is a <u>special type of memory</u> used in high-speed searching applications.</li><li>It determines how to handle incoming data frames by maintaining the MAC address table.</li></ul><li>A switch <i>populates</i> the MAC address table <i>based on</i> <b><u>source MAC addresses</u></b>.</li><li>When the <i>destination device</i> <i>responds</i>, the switch <u>adds</u> the <u>source MAC address</u> of the frame and the <u>port</u> where the frame was received to the MAC address table.</li></ul></div><div><i>Building the MAC address table:</i>&nbsp;</div><div><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The switch receives a frame from PC 1 on Port 1.&nbsp;</span><br></li></ul><div>&lt;image 1.2.1.2.1&gt;</div><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The switch examines the source MAC address and compares it to MAC address table.&nbsp;</span><br></li></ul></span><ol><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">If the address is not in the MAC address table, it associates the source MAC address of PC 1 with the ingress port (Port 1) in the MAC address table.</span><br></li></ul></ol><div>&lt;image 1.2.1.2.2&gt;</div><ol><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">If the MAC address table already has an entry for that source address, it resets the aging timer. An entry for a MAC address is typically kept for five minutes.&nbsp;</span><br></li></ul></ol><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">After the switch has recorded the source address information, the switch examines the destination MAC address.&nbsp;</span><br></li></ul></span><ol><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">If the destination address is not in the MAC table or if it‚Äôs a broadcast MAC address, as indicated by all Fs, the switch floods the frame to all ports, except the ingress port.</span><br></li></ul></ol><div>&lt;image 1.2.1.2.3&gt;</div><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The destination device (PC 3) replies to the frame with a unicast frame addressed to PC 1.</span><br></li></ul><div>&lt;image 1.2.1.2.4&gt;</div><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The switch enters the source MAC address of PC 3 and the port number of the ingress port into the address table. The destination address of the frame and its associated egress port is found in the MAC address table.</span><br></li></ul><div>&lt;image 1.2.1.2.5&gt;</div><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The switch can now forward frames between these source and destination devices without flooding, because it has entries in the address table that identify the associated ports.</span><br></li></ul><div>&lt;image 1.2.1.2.6&gt;</div></span></div><h2>Switching Forwarding Methods</h2><div>After introduced, LAN switches were able to move the <b>Layer 2 forwarding decisions</b> from software to application-specific-integrated circuits (<b>ASICs</b>).</div><div><i>ASICs</i> <u>reduce</u> the packet-handling time within the device, and <u>allow</u> the device to handle an increased number of ports without degrading performance.</div><div>This method was referred as <b>store-and-forward switching</b>.</div><div>&lt;image 1.2.1.3.1&gt;</div><div>Makes a <u>forwarding decision</u> on a frame after it has <u>received the entire frame</u> and <u>checked the frame</u> for errors using a mathematical error-checking mechanism known as a <b>cyclic redundancy check</b> (<b>CRC</b>).</div><div>The <b>cut-through</b> method <i>begins</i> forwarding process after the <u>destination MAC address</u> of an incoming frame and the <u>egress port</u> has been <u>determined</u>.</div><div>&lt;image 1.2.1.3.2&gt;</div><h2>Store-and-Forward Switching</h2><div><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">It is Cisco's </span><u style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"><i>primary LAN switching method</i></u><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">.</span><br></li><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">It </span><u style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">drops frames</u><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> that don't pass the </span><b style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">FCS check</b><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">,</span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">&nbsp;therefore doesn't forward invalid frames.</span><br></li><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The cut-through switch may forward invalid frames because there's no FCS check .</span></li></ul></ul></div><div>2 primary characteristics that distinguish it:</div><div><ul><li><b>Error Checking</b>&nbsp;</li><ul><li>On an incoming frame.</li><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">After receiving the entire frame on the ingress port, the switch compares the <b>frame-check-sequence</b> (<b>FCS</b>) value in the last field of the datagram against its own FCS calculations.</span><br></li><li>Process that <u>helps to ensure</u> that the frame is <u>free</u> of <u>physical and data-link errors</u>.</li><ul><li>If it's <b>error-free</b>, the <u>switch forwards the frame</u>.</li><li>Otherwise, <u>it's dropped</u>.</li></ul></ul><li><b>Automatic Buffering</b>&nbsp;</li><ul><li>The ingress port buffering process used store-and-forward switches <i>provides</i>&nbsp;flexibility to support <u>any mix of Ethernet speeds</u>.</li><li>With any <u>mismatch</u>&nbsp;<i>in speeds</i> between the <u>ingress and egress ports</u>, the switch stores the entire frame in a buffer, computes the FCS check, forwards it to the egress port buffer and then sends it.</li></ul></ul></div><div>&lt;image 1.2.1.4&gt;</div><h2>Cut-Through Switching</h2><div>An <u>advantage is the ability</u> of the switch to <i>start forwarding</i> a frame <i>earlier</i> than <i>store-and-forward</i>.</div><div>2 primary characteristics:</div><div><ul><li><b>Rapid Frame Forwarding</b>&nbsp;</li><ul><li>Can make forwarding decision as soon as it has looked up the destination MAC address of the frame in its MAC address table.</li><li>It doesn't have to wait for the rest of the frame to enter the ingress port before making its forwarding decision.</li><li>Can quickly decide whether it needs to examine a larger portion of a frame‚Äôs headers for additional filtering purposes.</li></ul></ul><ul><ul><li><u>Doesn't drop</u> most <b>invalid frames</b>. Frames with errors are forwarded to other segments of the network.</li><ul><li>If there's a high error rate (inv. frames), cut-through can have a <b>negative</b>&nbsp;impact on bandwidth, clogging up bandwidth with damaged and invalid frames.</li></ul></ul><li><b>Fragment Free</b>&nbsp;</li><ul><li><i><b>Modified</b></i>&nbsp;form of cut-through. The switch waits for the collision window (64 bytes) to pass before forwarding the frame.</li><li>Each frame will be <i>checked</i>&nbsp;into the <u>data field</u>&nbsp;to make sure no fragmentation has occurred.</li><ul><li><u>Better error</u> checking with practically no increase in latency.</li></ul></ul></ul></div><div><ul><ul><li><b>Lower latency</b> speed of cut-through makes it <b>more appropriate</b> for extremely demanding, <b>high-performance computing</b> (<b>HPC</b>) applications that require process-to-process latencies of 10 microseconds or less.</li></ul></ul></div><h2>Collision Domains</h2><div><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">In </span><b style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">hub-based Ethernet segments</b><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">, </span><u style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">network devices compete</u><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">&nbsp;for the medium, because </span><u style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">devices must take turns</u><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> when transmitting.</span><br></li><li>The network segments that share the same bandwidth between devices are known as collision domains.</li><ul><li>When 2 or more devices within that segment try to communicate at the same time, collisions may occur.</li></ul><li>It's <u>possible to use a switch</u> device, operating the <b>OSI data link layer,</b> to <b>divide a network into segments</b> and reduce the number of devices that compete for bandwidth.</li><li>When a switch is used, <u>each port represents a new segment</u>.</li><ul><li><i>Each segment</i> is a <i>new collision domain</i>.</li><li>More bandwidth is available to the devices on the segment.</li><li>Collisions in one collision domain don't interfere with other segments.</li><li>This is also <b>known as microsegmentation</b>.</li></ul><li>&lt;image 1.2.2.1&gt;</li></ul></div><h2>Broadcast Domains</h2><div><ul><li>Broadcast frames aren't filtered.</li><li>For other switches on the LAN to receive broadcast frames, switches must flood these frames out of all ports.</li><li>A collection of interconnected switches forms a single broadcast domain.</li><li>Only a <u>network device</u>, such as a router, can <u>divide</u> a <b>Layer 2 broadcast domain</b>. Routers are used to <u>segment both collision and broadcast domains</u>.</li><ul><li>When a device sends a Layer 2 broadcast, <u>destination MAC address</u> in the frame is set to all <b>binary ones</b>.</li><li>Received by all devices in the broadcast domain.</li></ul><li><u style=\"font-style: italic;\">Layer 2 broadcast domain</u>&nbsp;is referred as the&nbsp;<b>MAC broadcast domain</b>.</li><ul><li>It consists of all devices on the LAN that receive broadcast frames from a host.</li></ul></ul><div>&lt;image 1.2.2.2&gt;</div><ul><li>When <u>2 switches are connected</u> together, the <u>broadcast domain is increased</u>. In this case, a broadcast frame is forwarded to all connected ports on switch S1. S1 is connected to switch S2. S2 propagates to the other devices.</li></ul><h2>Alleviating Network Congestion</h2></div><div><ul><li><u>LAN switches</u> have <b>special characteristics</b> that make them effective alleviating network congestion.</li><ul><li>First:</li><ul><li>They <b>allow the segmentation of a LAN</b> into separate collision domains.</li><li><b><u>Each port</u> of the switch represents a separate collision domain</b> and <b>provides the full bandwidth</b> to the device or devices connected to that port.</li></ul><li>Second:</li><ul><li>They <b>provide full-duplex communication</b> between devices.</li><ul><li><i>Full-duplex connection can carry transmitted and received signals at the same time</i>.</li><li>This connections have dramatically increased LAN performance, and are required for 1 Gb/s Ethernet speeds and higher.</li></ul></ul></ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Switches interconnect segments, use a table of MAC addresses to determine the segment to which the frame is to be sent, and can lessen or eliminate collisions entirely.</span><br></li><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Some important characteristics of switches that contribute to alleviating network congestion:</span></li><ul><li><b style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">High port density</b><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> - Switches have high-port densities: 24- and 48-port switches are often just 1 rack unit (1.75 inches) in height and operate at speeds of 100 Mb/s, 1 Gb/s, and 10 Gb/s. Large enterprise switches may support many hundreds of ports.&nbsp;</span></li><li><b style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Large frame buffers</b><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> - The ability to store more received frames before having to start dropping them is useful, particularly when there may be congested ports to servers or other parts of the network.&nbsp;</span></li><li><b style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Port speed</b><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> - Depending on the cost of a switch, it may be possible to support a mixture of speeds. Ports of 100 Mb/s, and 1 or 10 Gb/s are common (100 Gb/s is also possible).&nbsp;</span></li><li><b style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Fast internal switching</b><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> - Having fast internal forwarding capabilities allows high performance. The method that is used may be a fast internal bus or shared memory, which affects the overall performance of the switch.&nbsp;</span></li><li><b style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Low per-port cost</b><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> - Switches provide high-port density at a lower cost. For this reason, LAN switches can accommodate network designs featuring fewer users per segment, therefore, increasing the average available bandwidth per user.</span></li></ul></ul></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div>","CDate":"Fri Aug 12 2016 11:33:56 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","MDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:47:28 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","Color":"#0086B3","Notebook":"4"},"8":{"id":8,"Title":"Chapter 2","Content":"<h1>Chapter 2</h1><h1>Basic Switching Concepts and Configuration</h1><h2>Switch Boot Sequence</h2><div>Powered on Cisco switch goes through the <b>boot sequence</b>:</div><div><ol><li>Switch loads a <b>power-on-self-test</b> (<b>POST</b>) program stored in ROM.</li><ul><li>It checks the CPU, DRAM, and the portion of the flash device that makes up the flash file system.</li></ul><li>It loads the <b>boot loader software</b>.</li><ul><li>Small program stored in ROM and is run immediately after POST successfully completes.</li></ul><li>The <i>boot loader</i> <u>performs</u> <i>low-level CPU initialization</i>.</li><ul><li>Initializes the CPU registers, which control where physical memory is mapped, the quantity of memory, and its speed.</li></ul><li>The <i>boot loader</i> <u>initializes</u> the <i>flash file system</i> on the system board.</li><li>The <i>boot loader</i> <u>locates</u>&nbsp;and <u>loads</u>&nbsp;a default IOS operating system software image into memory and hands control of the switch over to the IOS.</li></ol><div>The <i>boot loader</i>&nbsp;<u>finds</u> the <u>Cisco IOS image</u> on the switch as follows:</div></div><div><ol><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The switch attempts to automatically boot. Using info in the BOOT environment variable.</span><br></li><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">If </span><i style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">variable</i><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> not set, switch attempts to </span><b style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">load and execute the first executable file</b><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> it can.</span><br></li></ul><ol><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">It performs a recursive, depth-first search throughout the flash file system.</span><br></li></ul></ol><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The IOS operating system then initializes the interfaces using the Cisco IOS commands found in the configuration file, startup-config, which is stored in NVRAM.</span><br></li></ol></div><div><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/6cee1ad9-fc6d-4a18-bdc5-1ccc59ffccf2\" alt=\"https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-2dyjGODU0RI/V7-bLkXJPRI/AAAAAAAAOF8/__J5m-PsQ-cErtfbBj22KLdqcIq5iusKACLcB/s320/2.1.1.1.png\" data-url=\"https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-2dyjGODU0RI/V7-bLkXJPRI/AAAAAAAAOF8/__J5m-PsQ-cErtfbBj22KLdqcIq5iusKACLcB/s320/2.1.1.1.png\"><br></div><div><br></div><h2>Recovering From a System Crash</h2><div>The <i>boot loader</i>&nbsp;<b>provides access</b>&nbsp;into the switch if the operating system O.S. cannot be used because of missing or damaged system files. It has a <b>command-line</b>&nbsp; that <u>provides access</u>&nbsp;to the files stored in flash memory.</div><div>Through console&nbsp;</div><div><ul><li><b>Step 1</b>. <u>Connect</u> a PC by <u><i>console cable</i></u> to the switch console port. Configure terminal emulation software to connect to the switch.</li><li><b>Step 2</b>. <u>Unplug</u> the switch <u><i>power cord</i></u>.</li><li><b>Step 3</b>. <u>Reconnect</u> the power cord to the switch and, <u><i>within 15 seconds</i></u>, <i>press and hold</i> down the <b>Mode button</b> while the System LED is still <u>flashing green</u>.</li><li><b>Step 4</b>. <u>Continue pressing</u> the <i>Mode button</i> until the System LED turns briefly amber and then solid green; then release the <i>Mode button</i>.</li><li><b>Step 5</b>. The boot loader switch: prompt appears in the terminal emulation software on the PC.</li></ul></div><div><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/3be444fc-5d3a-4df5-8e0a-47641228566f\" alt=\"https://4.bp.blogspot.com/-gDhDXBEOHhE/V7-bLh_HiSI/AAAAAAAAOGA/1NvCvIkOrg0hTixV2zfC6f9oztvGFLUagCLcB/s1600/2.1.1.2.png\" data-url=\"https://4.bp.blogspot.com/-gDhDXBEOHhE/V7-bLh_HiSI/AAAAAAAAOGA/1NvCvIkOrg0hTixV2zfC6f9oztvGFLUagCLcB/s1600/2.1.1.2.png\"><br></div><h2>Switch LED Indicators</h2><div>You can use the switch LEDs to quickly monitor switch activity and its performance.</div><div>Purpose of the LED indicators and meaning of colors:</div><div><ul><li><b>System LED</b> - Shows whether the system is <u>receiving power</u> and is <u>functioning properly</u>. If the LED is off, it means the system is not powered on. If the LED is green, the system is operating normally. If the LED is amber, the system is receiving power but is not functioning properly.</li><li><b>Redundant Power System (RPS) LED</b> - Shows the <b><u>RPS status</u></b>. If the LED is off, the RPS is off or not properly connected. If the LED is green, the RPS is connected and ready to provide back-up power. If the LED is blinking green, the RPS is connected but is unavailable because it is providing power to another device. If the LED is amber, the RPS is in standby mode or in a fault condition. If the LED is blinking amber, the internal power supply in the switch has failed, and the RPS is providing power.</li><li><b>Port Status LED</b> - Indicates that the <u>port status mode is selected when the LED is <i>green</i></u>. This is the default mode. When selected, the port LEDs will display colors with different meanings. If the LED is off, there is no link, or the port was administratively shut down. If the LED is green, a link is present. If the LED is blinking green, there is activity and the port is sending or receiving data. If the LED is alternating green-amber, there is a link fault. If the LED is amber, the port is blocked to ensure a loop does not exist in the forwarding domain and is not forwarding data (typically, ports will remain in this state for the first 30 seconds after being activated). If the LED is blinking amber, the port is blocked to prevent a possible loop in the forwarding domain.</li><li><b>Port Duplex LED</b> - Indicates the <u>port duplex mode is selected</u> when the LED is <i>green</i>. When selected, port LEDs that are off are in half-duplex mode. If the port LED is green, the port is in full-duplex mode.</li><li><b>Port Speed LED</b> - Indicates the port speed mode is selected. When selected, the port LEDs will display colors with different meanings. If the LED is off, the port is operating at 10 Mb/s. If the LED is green, the port is operating at 100 Mb/s. If the LED is blinking green, the port is operating at 1000 Mb/s.</li><li><b>Power over Ethernet (PoE) Mode LED</b> - If PoE is supported; a PoE mode LED will be present. If the LED is <i><u>off</u></i>, it indicates the <u>PoE mode is not selected</u> and that none of the ports have been denied power or placed in a fault condition. If the LED is blinking amber, the PoE mode is not selected but at least one of the ports has been denied power, or has a PoE fault. If the LED is green, it indicates the PoE mode is selected and the port LEDs will display colors with different meanings. If the port LED is off, the PoE is off. If the port LED is green, the PoE is on. If the port LED is alternating green-amber, PoE is denied because providing power to the powered device will exceed the switch power capacity. If the LED is blinking amber, PoE is off due to a fault. If the LED is amber, PoE for the port has been disabled.</li></ul></div><div><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/b8e9762e-8438-460a-bba1-9aa3682b3680\" alt=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-vw1-u-HGCXs/V7-bLmhxbFI/AAAAAAAAOGE/XLs0V4t4gh05DITF7GC9WLymz6sq1n_fwCLcB/s1600/2.1.1.3.png\" data-url=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-vw1-u-HGCXs/V7-bLmhxbFI/AAAAAAAAOGE/XLs0V4t4gh05DITF7GC9WLymz6sq1n_fwCLcB/s1600/2.1.1.3.png\"><br></div><h2>Preparing for Basic Switch Management</h2><div>For remote management access[:long-arrow-right:] switch must be configured with an IP address and a subnet mask.</div><div>Must be configured with a default gateway.</div><div>The <b>switch virtual interface</b> (<b>SVI</b>) on S1 should be assigned an IP address. The <i>SVI</i> is a virtual interface, not a physical port on the switch.</div><div><img class=\"lazy\" src=\"blob:chrome-extension://pfdkhjakblfafmapniifbpkjblgolipd/9bb20b90-518a-4efe-b387-e75a22b151df\" alt=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/--H9hT6Hqp2k/V7-bL_pcGNI/AAAAAAAAOGI/p1edi0AAam4qr664YN71d_r1YFCZ3dCUQCLcB/s1600/2.1.1.4.png\" data-url=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/--H9hT6Hqp2k/V7-bL_pcGNI/AAAAAAAAOGI/p1edi0AAam4qr664YN71d_r1YFCZ3dCUQCLcB/s1600/2.1.1.4.png\"><br></div><h2>Configuring Basic Switch Management Access with IPv4&nbsp;</h2><div><ul><li><b>Step 1. Configure Management Interface</b>&nbsp;</li><ul><li>The <b>interface vlan 99 command</b> is used to enter interface configuration mode.</li><li>The <b>ip address command</b> is used to configure the IP address.</li><ul><li>S1(config)# vlan <i>vlan_id</i>&nbsp;</li><li>S1(config-vlan)# name <i>vlan_name</i>&nbsp;</li><li>S1(config-vlan)# exit</li><li>S1(config)# interface <i>interface_id</i>&nbsp;</li><li>S1(config-if)# switchport access vlan <i>vlan_id</i>&nbsp;</li></ul></ul><li><b>Step 2. Configure Default Gateway</b>&nbsp;</li><ul><li><br></li></ul><li><b>Step 3. Verify Configuration</b>&nbsp;</li><ul><li>The show ip interface brief command is useful when determining the status of both physical and virtual interfaces.</li></ul></ul></div><div>&lt;image 2.1.1.5.1&gt;</div><div>&lt;image 2.1.1.5.2&gt;</div><div>&lt;image 2.1.1.5.3&gt;</div><h2>Duplex Communication</h2><div><ul><li><b>Full-duplex communication</b> improves the performance of a switched LAN.</li><li><b>Half-duplex communication</b> is unidirectional.</li></ul></div><div>&lt;image 2.1.2.1&gt;</div><h2>Configure Switch Ports at the Physical Layer</h2><div><ul><li><b>Duplex and Speed</b>&nbsp;</li><ul><li><br></li></ul></ul></div><div>&lt;image 2.1.2.2.1&gt;</div><div>&lt;image 2.1.2.2.2&gt;</div><h2>Auto-MDIX</h2><div><ul><li>Using the <b>automatic medium-dependent interface crossover</b> (<b>auto-MDIX</b>) feature on an interface eliminates this problem.</li></ul></div><div>&lt;image 2.1.2.3.1&gt;</div><div>&lt;image 2.1.2.3.2&gt;</div><div>&lt;image 2.1.2.3.3&gt;</div><h2>Verifying Switch Port Configuration</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.1.2.4.1&gt;</div><div>&lt;image 2.1.2.4.2&gt;</div><div>&lt;image 2.1.2.4.3&gt;</div><h2>Network Access Layer</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.1.2.5&gt;</div><h2>Troubleshooting Network Access Layer Issues</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.1.2.6&gt;</div><h2>SSH Operation</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.2.1.1&gt;</div><h2>Configure SSH</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.2.1.2&gt;</div><h2>Verifying SSH</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.2.1.3&gt;</div><h2>Common Security Attacks: MAC Address Flooding</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.2.2.1&gt;</div><h2>Common Security Attacks: DHCP Spoofing</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.2.2.2&gt;</div><h2>Common Security Attacks: Leveraging CDP</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.2.2.3&gt;</div><div>&lt;image 2.2.2.4&gt;</div><h2>Best Practices</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.2.3.1&gt;</div><h2>Network Security Tools and Testing</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.2.3.2&gt;</div><h2>Network Security Audits</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.2.3.3&gt;</div><h2>Secure Unused Ports</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.2.4.1&gt;</div><h2>DHCP Snooping</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.2.4.2&gt;</div><h2>Port Security: Operation</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.2.4.3&gt;</div><h2>Port Security: Violation Modes</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.2.4.4&gt;</div><h2>Port Security: Configuring</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.2.4.5&gt;</div><h2>Port Security: Verifying</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.2.4.6&gt;</div><h2>Ports in Error Disabled State</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.2.4.7&gt;</div><h2>Network Time Protocol (NTP)</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;image 2.2.4.8&gt;</div>","CDate":"Thu Aug 18 2016 23:40:32 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","MDate":"Sun Sep 18 2016 15:21:48 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","Color":"#FF304F","Notebook":"4"},"10":{"id":10,"Title":"Chapter 3","Content":"<h1>Chapter 3</h1><h1>VLANs</h1><h2>VLAN Definitions</h2><div><ul><li>They provide segmentation and organizational flexibility.</li><li>Way to group devices within a LAN.</li><ul><li>A group of devices within a VLAN communicate as if they were attached to the same wire.</li><li>Each one is considered a <u>separate logical network</u>.</li></ul><li>Based on <u>logical connections</u>, instead of physical.</li><li>They allow an admin to <u>segment networks</u> based on:</li><ul><li>Function, project team, or application.</li><li>No regard for the physical location of user or device.</li></ul><li><b>Devices</b> act as if they are in their own independent network, even if there's a common infrastructure.</li><li>Any switch port can belong to a VLAN.</li><li><b>Packets</b> are forwarded and flooded only within the VLAN where are sourced.</li><ul><li>Packets destined for stations that do not belong to the VLAN must be forwarded through a device that supports routing.</li></ul></ul></div><div>&lt;3.1.1.1&gt;</div><h2>Benefits of VLANs</h2><div><ul><li><b>Security -</b>&nbsp;Groups that have sensitive data are separated from the rest of the network.</li><li><b>Cost reduction -</b>&nbsp;Reduced need for expensive network upgrades. More efficient use of existing bandwidth and uplinks.</li><li><b>Better performance -</b>&nbsp;<i>Dividing</i> flat <b><i>Layer 2</i></b> into multiple logical workgroups (broadcast domains) <i>reduces</i> unnecessary traffic on the network and boosts performance.</li><li><b>Shrink broadcast domains -</b>&nbsp;Dividing into VLANs reduces the number of devices in the broadcast domain.</li><li><b>Improved IT staff efficiency -</b>&nbsp;Users with similar network requirements share the same VLAN.</li><ul><li>Easier for IT staff to identify the function of a VLAN by giving it an appropriate name.</li></ul><li><b>Simpler project and application management -</b>&nbsp;VLANs aggregate users and network devices to support business or geographic requirements.</li><ul><li>Separate functions makes managing easier.</li></ul></ul></div><div><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">VLAN design must take into consideration the implementation of a </span><b style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">hierarchical network-addressing scheme</b><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">.</span><br></li><ul><li>IP network numbers are applied to network segments or VLANs in an orderly fashion that takes a <u><i>network as a whole</i></u> into consideration.</li></ul></ul></div><div>&lt;3.1.1.2&gt;</div><h2>Types of VLANs</h2><div><ul><li><b>Data VLAN</b></li><ul><li>A VLAN configured to carry user-generated traffic. A VLAN carrying voice or management traffic <strike>wouldn't be a data VLAN</strike>.</li><ul><li>Common practice to <u><i>separate</i></u>&nbsp;voice and management from data traffic.</li></ul></ul><li><b>Default VLAN</b></li><ul><li><u>All switch ports</u> become <i>part of the <b>default VLAN</b></i> after the initial boot up of a switch loading the default configuration.</li><ul><li><b>Ports in</b> the default VLAN are <i>part of</i> the same <i>broadcast domain</i>.</li><ul><li>Any device connected to any switch port can communicate with other devices on other switch ports.</li></ul></ul></ul><li><b>Native VLAN</b></li><ul><li>Is assigned to an 802.1Q trunk port.</li><ul><li>Trunk ports are links between switches that support the transmission of traffic associated with more than one VLAN.</li></ul><li><b>802.1Q trunk</b> ports support traffic coming from many VLANs (<b>tagged traffic</b>), and traffic that does not come from a VLAN (<b>untagged traffic</b>).</li><ul><li><b>Tagged</b> refers to a <b>4-byte tag</b> inserted within the original Ethernet frame header, specifying the VLAN where it belongs.</li><li><i>802.1Q trunk</i>&nbsp; places untagged on the native, by default VLAN 1.</li></ul><li>Defined to maintain backward compatibility with untagged traffic common to legacy LAN scenarios.</li><ul><li>Common identifier on opposite ends of a trunk link.</li></ul><li><b><i>Best practice</i></b> to configure the native as an unused VLAN, distinct from VLAN 1 and other VLANs.</li></ul><li><b>Management VLAN</b></li><ul><li><i>Any VLAN</i> configured to <u>access the management</u> capabilities of a switch.</li><ul><li>VLAN 1 is the one by default.</li></ul><li>The switch virtual interface (<b>SVI</b>) of that VLAN is assigned an IP address and subnet mask, allowing the switch to be managed via HTTP, Telnet, SSH, or SNMP.</li><ul><li>VLAN 1 is the default VLAN, VLAN 1 would be a bad choice for the management VLAN.</li></ul><li>Having more than one increases exposure to network attacks.</li></ul></ul></div><div>&lt;3.1.1.3&gt;</div><h2>Voice VLANs</h2><div><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Separate VLAN is needed to support Voice over IP (VoIP). VoIP traffic requires:</span><br></li><ul><li>Assured bandwidth to ensure voice quality.</li><li>Transmission priority over other types of network traffic.</li><li>Ability to be routed around congested areas on the network.</li><li>Delay of less than 150 ms across the network.</li></ul><li>The entire network has to be designed to support VoIP.</li></ul></div><div>&lt;3.1.1.4&gt;</div><h2>VLAN Trunks</h2><div><ul><li>A <b>trunk</b> is a <b>point-to-point</b> between <u>two network devices</u> that carries more than one VLAN.</li><li>A <i>VLAN trunk</i> extends VLANs across an entire network.</li><li>VLANs wouldn't be useful without VLAN trunks.</li><ul><li>They allow all VLAN traffic to <u>propagate between switches</u>, so that devices (same VLAN, different switch) can communicate <i>without</i> a router.</li></ul><li>A <i>VLAN trunk</i> does not belong to a specific VLAN. Conduit for multiple VLANs.</li></ul></div><div>&lt;3.1.2.1&gt;</div><h2>Controlling Broadcast Domains with VLANs</h2><div><ul><li><b>Network without VLANs</b>&nbsp;</li><ul><li>When a switch receives a broadcast frame, it forwards the frame out all the other ports.</li><li>Eventually the entire network receives the broadcast, the network is one broadcast domain.</li></ul></ul><div>&lt;3.1.2.2.1&gt;</div><ul><li><b>Network with VLANs</b>&nbsp;</li><ul><li>The network is segmented using VLANs.</li><li>When a broadcast frame is sent, the switch forwards the frame only to those switch ports configured to support the VLAN \"X\".</li><li>When VLANs are implemented on a switch, the transmission of unicast, multicast, and broadcast traffic from a host in a <i>particular VLAN</i> are restricted to the devices that are in <i>that VLAN</i>.</li></ul></ul></div><div>&lt;3.1.2.2.2&gt;</div><h2>Tagging Ethernet Frames for VLAN Identification</h2><div><ul><li>When <i>Ethernet frames</i> are placed <i>on a trunk</i>, <u>information</u> about the VLANs to which they belong must be <u>added</u>.</li><li><b>Tagging</b>&nbsp;is accomplished by using the <b>IEEE 802.1Q <i>header</i></b>.</li><ul><li>The <i>4-byte tag</i> inserted.</li></ul><li><i>Switch</i> receives a <i>frame</i> on a <b><i>port configed</i></b> in <b>access mode </b>and a<b> VLAN</b>, it <i>inserts</i> a <u>VLAN tag</u> in the <i>frame header</i>, <i>recalculates </i><u>FCS</u>, and <i>sends</i> the tagged frame <u>out of a trunk port</u>.</li><li><b>VLAN Tag Field Details:</b>&nbsp;</li><ul><li><b>Type -</b> &nbsp;A 2-byte value called the <b>tag protocol ID</b> (<b>TPID</b>) <b>value</b>. For Ethernet, it is set to hexadecimal 0x8100.</li><li><b>User priority -</b> A 3-bit value that supports level or service implementation.</li><li><b>Canonical Format Identifier (CFI) -</b> A 1-bit identifier that enables Token Ring frames to be carried across Ethernet links.</li><li><b>VLAN ID (VID) -</b> A 12-bit VLAN identification number that supports up to 4096 VLAN IDs.</li></ul><li>Switch recalculates the FCS values and inserts the new FCS.</li></ul></div><div>&lt;3.1.2.3&gt;</div><h2>Native VLANs and 802.1Q Tagging</h2><div><ul><li><b>Tagged Frames on the Native VLAN</b>&nbsp;</li><ul><li>Some devices add a <i>VLAN tag</i> to <i>native VLAN traffic</i>.</li><li><i>Control traffic</i> <u>sent</u> on the native VLAN should <b>not</b> be <strike>tagged</strike>.</li><ul><li>If an <i>802.1Q trunk port</i> <u>receives</u> a tagged frame with the <u>VLAN ID</u> the <u>same as</u> the <u>native VLAN</u>, it <b>drops the frame</b>.</li><li>So configure devices so that they <u>don't</u> <strike>send tagged frames</strike> on the <i>native VLAN</i>.</li></ul></ul><li><b>Untagged Frames on the Native VLAN</b>&nbsp;</li><ul><li>When a Cisco switch trunk port receives untagged frames (unusual in a well-designed network), it forwards those frames to the native VLAN.</li><ul><li><b>No devices</b> associated with the <i>native VLAN</i> and <b>no other trunk ports</b>, <i>frame is dropped</i>.</li></ul><li>When configuring an 802.1Q trunk port, a default Port VLAN ID (PVID) is assigned the value of the native VLAN ID.</li><ul><li>Untagged traffic coming in or out of the 802.1Q port is forwarded based on the PVID value.</li></ul></ul></ul></div><div>&lt;3.1.2.4&gt;</div><h2>Voice VLAN Tagging</h2><div>Recall that to support VoIP, a separate voice VLAN is required.</div><div><ul><li>An <u>access port</u> used to <u>connect</u> a <i>Cisco IP phone</i>&nbsp;can be <u>configured</u> to <u>use 2 separate VLANS</u>: one for <i><u>voice traffic</u></i> and another for <i><u>data traffic</u></i> from a device attached to the phone.</li><li>The Cisco IP Phone contains an integrated three-port 10/100 switch. The ports provide dedicated connections to these devices:</li><ul><li><b>Port 1</b> <i>connects</i> to the switch or other VoIP device.</li><li><b>Port 2</b> is an <i>internal 10/100 interface</i> that carries the IP phone traffic.</li><li><b>Port 3</b> (<b>access port</b>) <i>connects</i> to a PC or other device.</li></ul><li>On the switch, the access is configured to send <b>Cisco Discovery Protocol</b> (<b>CDP</b>) <b>packets</b> that instruct an attached IP phone to send voice traffic to the switch in one of three ways, depending on the type of traffic:</li><ul><li>In a <i>voice VLAN</i> <i>tagged</i> with a Layer 2 class of service (CoS) priority value.</li><li>In an <i>access VLAN tagged</i> with a Layer 2 CoS priority value.</li><li>In an <i>access VLAN, untagged</i> (no Layer 2 CoS priority value).</li></ul></ul></div><div>&lt;3.1.2.5.1&gt;</div><div><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"><b>Sample Configuration</b>&nbsp;</span></li></ul><div>&lt;3.1.2.5.2&gt;</div></div><div>&lt;3.1.2.6.1&gt;</div><div>&lt;3.1.2.6.2&gt;</div><div>&lt;3.1.2.6.3&gt;</div><h2>VLAN Ranges on Catalyst Switches</h2><div><ul><li>Different Cisco Catalyst switches support various numbers of VLANs.</li><li>The number of supported VLANs is large enough to accommodate the needs of most organizations.</li></ul></div><div>&lt;3.2.1.1&gt;</div><div><ul><li><b>Normal Range VLANs</b>&nbsp;</li><ul><li>Used in <u>small- and medium-sized business</u> and enterprise networks.</li><li>Identified by a VLAN ID between 1 and 1005.</li><li>IDs 1002 through 1005 are reserved for Token Ring and FDDI VLANs.</li><li>IDs 1 and 1002 to 1005 are <u>automatically created</u> and cannot be removed.</li><li><u>Configurations are stored within a <i>VLAN database file</i></u>, called <b>vlan.dat</b>. It is located in the flash memory of the switch.</li><li>The <b>VLAN Trunking Protocol</b> (<b>VTP</b>), which helps manage VLAN configurations between switches, <u>can only learn and store <i>normal range VLANs</i></u>.</li></ul><li><b>Extended Range VLANs</b>&nbsp;</li><ul><li>Enable service providers to extend their infrastructure to a greater number of customers. Global enterprises generally.</li><li>Are identified by a VLAN ID between 1006 and 4094.</li><li><u>Configurations</u> are not <strike>written</strike> to the vlan.dat file.</li><li>Support fewer VLAN features than normal range VLANs.</li><li>Are, by default, saved in the running configuration file.</li><li>VTP does not learn extended range VLANs.</li></ul></ul></div><h2>Creating a VLAN</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.2.1.2.1&gt;</div><div>&lt;3.2.1.2.2&gt;</div><div>&lt;3.2.1.2.3&gt;</div><h2>Assigning Ports to VLANs</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.2.1.3&gt;</div><h2>Changing VLAN Port Membership</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.2.1.4&gt;</div><h2>Deleting VLANs</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.2.1.5&gt;</div><h2>Verifying VLAN Information</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.2.1.6&gt;</div><h2>Configuring IEEE 802.1Q Trunk Links</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.2.2.1&gt;</div><h2>Resetting the Trunk to Default State</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.2.2.2&gt;</div><h2>Verifying Trunk Configuration</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.2.2.3&gt;</div><h2>Introduction to DTP</h2><div>Dynamic desirable is the default, NOT auto. If you connect switches and they form a trunk, then they are automatically in desirable. Auto waits for the other, so if the switches are in auto, they will keep waiting.</div><div>&lt;3.2.3.1.1&gt;</div><div>&lt;3.2.3.1.2&gt;</div><h2>Negotiated Interface Modes</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.2.3.2&gt;</div><div>&lt;3.2.3.3&gt;</div><h2>IP Addressing Issues with VLAN</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.2.4.1&gt;</div><h2>Missing VLANs</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.2.4.2&gt;</div><h2>Introduction to Troubleshooting Trunks</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.2.4.3&gt;</div><h2>Common Problems with Trunks</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.2.4.4&gt;</div><h2>Trunk Mode Mismatches</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.2.4.5&gt;</div><h2>Incorrect VLAN List</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.2.4.6&gt;</div><h2>Switch Spoofing Attack</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.3.1.1&gt;</div><h2>Double-Tagging Attack</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.3.1.2&gt;</div><h2>PVLAN Edge</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.3.1.3&gt;</div><div>&lt;3.3.1.4&gt;</div><h2>VLAN Design Guidelines</h2><div><br></div><div>&lt;3.3.2.1&gt;</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div>","CDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:46:58 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","MDate":"Sun Sep 18 2016 14:42:10 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","Color":"#FC9C00","Notebook":"4"},"11":{"id":11,"Title":"Chapter 4","Content":"<h1>Chapter 4</h1><h1>Routing Concepts</h1><div><br></div>","CDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:47:32 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","MDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:49:49 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","Color":"#FF304F","Notebook":"4"},"12":{"id":12,"Title":"Chapter 5","Content":"<h1>Chapter 5</h1><h1>Inter-VLAN Routing</h1><div><br></div>","CDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:47:36 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","MDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:49:22 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","Color":"#63B75D","Notebook":"4"},"13":{"id":13,"Title":"Chapter 6","Content":"<h1>Chapter 6</h1><h1>Static Routing</h1><div><br></div>","CDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:47:37 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","MDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:50:08 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","Color":"#9A30DD","Notebook":"4"},"14":{"id":14,"Title":"Chapter 7","Content":"<h1>Chapter 7</h1><h1>Routing Dynamically</h1><div><br></div>","CDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:47:37 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","MDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:50:18 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","Color":"#F06868","Notebook":"4"},"15":{"id":15,"Title":"Chapter 8","Content":"<h1>Chapter 8</h1><h1>Single-Area OSPF</h1>","CDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:47:38 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","MDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:50:33 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","Color":"#41B3D3","Notebook":"4"},"16":{"id":16,"Title":"Chapter 9","Content":"<h1>Chapter 9</h1><h1>Access Control Lists</h1><div><br></div>","CDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:47:39 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","MDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:50:47 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","Color":"#ED5784","Notebook":"4"},"17":{"id":17,"Title":"Chapter 10","Content":"<h1>Chapter 10</h1><h1>DHCP</h1><div><br></div>","CDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:47:39 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","MDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:50:59 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","Color":"#76E7C7","Notebook":"4"},"18":{"id":18,"Title":"Chapter 11","Content":"<h1>Chapter 11</h1><h1>Network Address Translation for IPv4</h1><div><br></div>","CDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:47:40 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","MDate":"Sun Aug 28 2016 14:49:18 GMT-0500 (Hora de verano central (M√©xico))","Color":"#B7569A","Notebook":"4"}}}
